@article{Devriendt2017a,
abstract = {The $\delta$18O of ostracod valves is widely used to infer water $\delta$18O and temperature. However, ostracod $\delta$18O appears sensitive to other environmental variables. In addition, there is species-dependent ostracod calcite 18O enrichment, relative to slowly precipitated inorganic calcite under the same conditions. Together these uncertainties complicate ostracod paleoclimate reconstructions. This study presents a new understanding of the causes of ostracod $\delta$18O variations based on a global database of published ostracod $\delta$18O values in lake, marine and coastal environments, and from culture experiments. The database includes associated field/experiment host water parameters including temperature (−1 to 32 °C), water $\delta$18O (−13.2‰ to 4.3‰ VSMOW), pH (6.9–10.4), salinity (0–72 g/kg), calcite saturation states (0.6–26), and dissolved inorganic carbon concentration [DIC] (0.9–54.3 mmol/kg). The data show that: (1) the $\delta$18O of marine and non-marine ostracods reflects the 18O/16O of the sum of host water CO32− and HCO3− ions. For example, at a given temperature, the $\delta$18O of non-marine ostracods decreases by 4‰ to 6‰ as [CO32−]/[DIC] reaches 70{\%}, depending on the ostracod species. In low [CO32−]/[DIC] settings (i.e. high HCO3−/CO32−), ostracod 18O/16O is close to the 18O/16O of HCO3− ions, which explains why on average ostracod $\delta$18O is higher than the $\delta$18O of inorganic calcite precipitated slowly under the same conditions. (2) Taxonomic offsets in ostracod $\delta$18O vary with the host water [CO32−]/[DIC]. In environments where HCO3− ≫ CO32− (i.e. most freshwater lakes), the 18O/16O of Candonids is indistinguishable from the 18O/16O of HCO3− ions (difference of 0.10 ± 0.16‰) while the 18O/16O of Cyprids is lower than the 18O/16O of HCO3− ions by −0.77‰ to −0.32‰, Cytherids by −0.88 ± 0.29‰, and Limnocytherids by −1.12 ± 0.05‰. (3) The sensitivity of ostracod $\delta$18O to [CO32−]/[DIC] also varies with taxonomy. For each percent increase in [CO32−]/[DIC], Candonids $\delta$18O decreases by −0.098 ± 0.024‰, Cyprids by −0.075 ± 0.004‰, Cytherids by −0.057 ± 0.012‰, and Limnocytherids by −0.058 ± 0.005‰. (4) The similarity in 18O/16O between ostracod calcite and the sum of host water ‘HCO3− and CO32−' (despite species-specific offsets) suggests rapid precipitation of a finite DIC pool in the ostracod calcifying fluid. We propose an ostracod $\delta$18O model whereby the more negative the 18O/16O of a given species relative to the sum of CO32− and HCO3−, the greater the isotopic equilibrium between the DIC pool and H2O in the ostracod calcifying fluid. (5) Higher host water salinities and pH induce higher [CO32−]/[DIC], resulting in lower ostracod $\delta$18O, which explains the variable salinity and pH effects on ostracod $\delta$18O. Our database and ostracod $\delta$18O model shows that ostracod $\delta$18O records from closed basin environments likely reflect high or variable [CO32−]/[DIC], rather than water temperature and $\delta$18O alone. Our study reconciles contradictory observations of controls on ostracod $\delta$18O and paves the way for improved paleo-environmental interpretations and reconstructions of past water [CO32−]/[DIC].},
