c parasequences (e.g. Capitan shelf parasequences or Loferites). Facies similarities such as Renalcis mounds and flaser-bedded intertidal ribbon rock reflect anomalous oceanic conditions resulting in low biodiversity and low intensity of bioturbation after the end-Permian extinction. Similarities in parasequence stacking patterns reflect low-amplitude, high-frequency sea-level fluctuations resulting from green-house conditions common to the Early Palaeozoic and Early Triassic. ?? 2001 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved.},
