@article{Anderson1977,
abstract = {Detailed examination of the test morphology, organic layers and microstructure of G. menardii (d'Orbigny) elucidated the mode of wall construction and chamber formation. The organic layers and matrix within the test probably play an important role in the calcification process. Calcification of a new chamber wall probably starts with the secretion of 2 calcite layers on either side of the primary organic membrane (POM). These calcite layers are bounded by inner and outer organic layers formed by the inner and outer cytoplasm, respectively. Additional calcite layers are secreted between successive organic layers. The calcite layers including the calcite crust on the distal side of the POM are thicker than those on the proximal side. An inner organic lining (IOL) is the last organic layer to be formed on the inner test surface and grows thicker with age. It serves as a protective lining and may or may not aid in calcite secretion. The incipient wall may be completely calcified while still lacking pores. Numerous micropores are subsequently developed by partial resorption of the calcified wall in regions where regular pores will be formed. The pores are initially irregular in outline and occur over the entire chamber surface including the keel. Surface ridges probably reflect the direction of protoplasmic streaming on the test surface and pustules may be anchoring points for rhizopodia.},
