@article{Rudat1978,
abstract = {Ion-to-electron converter relative electron yield factors have been determined and tabulated for 68 atomic, 23 dimer and 27 monoxide positive ions striking the detector at 46.5 keV using a CAMECA IMS-300 ion microanalyzer and a Faraday cup as an ion current reference. Periodic oscillations in the relative yields are similar to those reported for atomic ions at lower impact energies on electron multipliers. A correlation between monoxide ion yields and atomic ion yields has been shown; the monoxide ion of an element has an electron yield which exceeds that of the corresponding atomic ion yield by a constant factor. A similar correlation has been shown for the dimer ions, with a different offset. The effect of using uncorrected signals in some quantitative analysis methods using SIMS is illustrated, showing that as much as 100{\%} error may arise from this source alone. The use of uncorrected monoxide ion signals in these schemes is similarly shown to induce errors caused by the higher monoxide ion yields compared to atomic ions. {\textcopyright} 1978.},
