abstract = {The nucleation and growth processes of particles and crystals from$\backslash$naqueous systems are actively investigated and occasionally open to$\backslash$ndebate because multistep nucleation and prenucleation events often$\backslash$nexist. This study demonstrates that time-resolved Raman spectroscopic$\backslash$nmeasurements can provide complementary and useful information on the$\backslash$nnucleation and growth of particles and crystals from homogeneous and$\backslash$nheterogeneous systems at different pressure-temperature conditions.$\backslash$nThree minerals were chosen for this study: siderite, magnesite, and$\backslash$ncalcite, three carbonate minerals that are widespread in geological$\backslash$nenvironments and have numerous industrial and medical applications. As$\backslash$nexpected, siderite and calcite can rapidly form via an amor-phous$\backslash$nprecursor when using concentrated solutions of reactants directly mixed$\backslash$nat ambient temperature (similar to 25 degrees C) and pressure (similar$\backslash$nto 1 bar) (i.e., via spinodal decomposition or when energetic barrier is$\backslash$nclose to zero). In addition, calcium carbonate clusters and/or probably$\backslash$nalso amorphous calcium carbonate (ACC) were detected in the first 5 min$\backslash$nprior to calcite nucleation in a Ca(OH)(2)-H2O-CO2 concentrated slurry$\backslash$nat 25 degrees C and 50 bar. The calcite and siderite crystals, nucleated$\backslash$nfrom their respective amorphous phases, grow by oriented aggregation of$\backslash$ncrystalline nanoparticles leading to porous spherical$\backslash$nsiderite-mesocrystals or nonporous rhombohedral calcite crystals after$\backslash$n24 h of reaction, as deduced from field emission scanning electron$\backslash$nmicroscopy images and X-ray diffraction analyses. Moreover, the$\backslash$npossibility of an Ostwald ripening mechanism contributing to crystal$\backslash$ngrowth is not excluded. Conversely, magnesite formation was not detected$\backslash$nby Raman spectroscopy at ambient room temperature; only nesquehonite$\backslash$n(MgCO3 center dot 3H(2)O) and dypingite (Mg-5(CO3)(4)center$\backslash$ndot(OH)(2)center dot 5H(2)O) were formed, depending on the reacting$\backslash$nsolution chemistry. These two minerals transform rapidly into$\backslash$nhydromagnesite (Mgs(CO3)(4)-(OH)(2)center dot 4H(2)O) by a heat-aging$\backslash$nstep at 50 degrees C. In fact, magnesite formation (MgCO3: anhydrous Mg$\backslash$ncarbonate) was only measured under hydrothermal conditions (e.g., 90$\backslash$ndegrees C and 50 bar of initial CO, pressure), and systematically a$\backslash$ntransient crystalline phase such as hydromagnesite was observed prior to$\backslash$nmagnesite nucleation and growth at the investigated conditions. This$\backslash$nconfirms that crystalline phases (not necessarily polymorphs) can also$\backslash$nact as precursors during nucleation and growth of more stable phases.$\backslash$nThe fact that direct nucleation of magnesite from ionic solutions and$\backslash$nslurries at ambient temperature is not observed is probably due to the$\backslash$nhigh level of hydration of Mg ions in aqueous systems.},
