87Sr/86Sr ratios of the Dreissena sediment (mean 0.71005) are probably caused by Sr derived from detrital mica. Carbonates are accompanied by blocks and crusts composed of pyrite. The framboidal sulphide exhibits a palisade-like fabric with framboids arranged to parallel pillars. Sulphur isotopic ratios ($\delta$34S) ranging from +16.8 to + 19.7‰ CDT indicate that the sulphur derives not from the34S-depleted H2S of the water column or the uppermost sediment layers. Most likely, pyrite formed in the lacustrine sediments after the first incursion of Mediterranean seawater. {\textcopyright} 2001 Elsevier Science B.V.},
