entary sequence with variable input of organic matter. Thus, the study of dolomite layers in ancient organic carbon-rich sedimentary sequences can provide a useful window into the palaeo-dynamics of the deep biosphere.},
author = {Meister, Patrick and McKenzie, Judith a. and Vasconcelos, Crisogono and Bernasconi, Stefano and Frank, Martin and Gutjahr, Marcus and Schrag, Daniel P.},
doi = {10.1111/j.1365-3091.2007.00870.x},
file = {:home/nicola/.local/share/data/Mendeley Ltd./Mendeley Desktop/Downloaded/Meister et al. - 2007 - Dolomite formation in the dynamic deep biosphere Results from the Peru Margin.pdf:pdf},
isbn = {0037-0746$\backslash$rISI:000249664200002},
issn = {00370746},
journal = {Sedimentology},
keywords = {Carbon isotopes,Deep biosphere,Dolomite,Peru Margin,Strontium isotopes,Sulphate-methane interface},
