@article{Crowley1993,
abstract = {Observational and modeling studies relevant to climate change on tectonic time scales are reviewed. Probably the most significant climate result from this time scale involves inferences about nearly ice-free conditions for some intervals of earth history. Some additional results suggest relatively rapid transitions between climate states. Modeling studies indicate that although tectonic changes significantly modify the atmosphere and ocean circulation, in most cases such modifications do not appear to be sufficient to explain ice-free climates. Increased atmospheric CO2 levels (5-10 × present values?) may be needed to completely reconcile models and data. Although the CO2 paradigm has received widespread attention in the last few years, the results summarized herein indicate that CO2 is only one of several important factors influencing climate. I believe the time is appropriate for contemplating climate change on tectonic time scales in terms of a "post-CO2 synthesis," in which direct tectonic factors are approximately equal in importance to CO2 fluctuations. In the last few years, modeling studies have progressed from a state of virtually no work on the topic to one where the models are in some respect ahead of the observations, in the sense that data have not been compiled to test even some of the most basic model predictions. In particular, information is needed on past atmospheric CO2 levels, tropical sea-surface temperatures, seasonality of continental interiors, and locations and production rates of deep-waters. Initial steps are being taken to integrate observational and modeling activities on tectonic time scales, and some of these shortcomings may be rectified over the next few years. {\textcopyright} 1993.},
