ng the resulting riverine particulates with FeHRdepleted$\backslash$r$\backslash$nglacial particulates. Preliminary measurements of inner shore sediments are$\backslash$r$\backslash$nconsistent with (i) above. Phanerozoic and modern normal marine sediments have$\backslash$r$\backslash$nsimilar iron speciation characteristics, which implies the existence of a long-term$\backslash$r$\backslash$nsteady state for the iron cycle. This steady state could be maintained by a glacioeustatic$\backslash$r$\backslash$nfeedback, where FeHR-enriched riverine particulates are either more effectively trapped$\backslash$r$\backslash$nwhen sealevel is high (small ice masses, diminished glacial erosion), or are mixed with$\backslash$r$\backslash$ngreater masses of FeHR-depleted glacial particulates when sealevel is low (large ice$\backslash$r$\backslash$nmasses, enhanced glacial erosion). Further important controls on the steady state for FeHR operate through the formation of euxinic sediments and ironstones, which also$\backslash$r$\backslash$nprovide sealevel-dependent sinks for FeHR-enriched sediment.},
