ousand in the Wordian. A tentative explanation, as in the case of oxygen, is based on the proposition that the semi-enclosed Delaware Basin was likely stratified, with sequestration of the C-13-depleted carbon to the deeper water layers and a complementary C-13 enrichment in the upper oxygenated layer. The coeval open ocean water DIC may have been similar to that of the remainder of the Permian interval, at similar to 4 parts per thousand, as indicated by whole rock carbonate samples from Oman, Sicily, and Iran. In the latest Permian, the trend mimics the well-known delta(13)C drop at the Permian/Triassic boundary. (c) 2005 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.},
